{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01T8CUzrbnTY5JaeH1wZcEjb","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n3\tstatus: complete\n4\tinputDocuments:\n5\t  - prd.md (parallel execution PRD, 30 FRs, 13 NFRs)\n6\t  - architecture-parallel-execution.md (8 decisions)\n7\t  - ux-design-parallel-execution.md (multi-lane TUI UX)\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\t# codeharness - Epic Breakdown (Parallel Execution)\n11\t\n12\t## Overview\n13\t\n14\tThis document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for codeharness parallel execution, decomposing 30 FRs into implementable stories.\n15\t\n16\t## Requirements Inventory\n17\t\n18\t### Functional Requirements\n19\t\n20\t- FR1: User can define story_flow, epic_flow, and execution sections in workflow YAML\n21\t- FR2: System can parse and validate the hierarchical flow model with backward compatibility\n22\t- FR3: System can execute story-level flow for each story within an epic\n23\t- FR4: System can execute epic-level flow when all stories in an epic complete\n24\t- FR5: System can schedule epics according to epic_strategy (parallel or sequential)\n25\t- FR6: System can create a git worktree for each parallel epic dispatch\n26\t- FR7: System can create a git branch per epic\n27\t- FR8: System can execute stories sequentially within a worktree\n28\t- FR9: System can manage a lane pool limited by max_parallel\n29\t- FR10: System can detect epic independence for parallel scheduling\n30\t- FR11: System can clean up worktrees and branches after epic completion\n31\t- FR12: System can merge an epic's branch into main after epic completion\n32\t- FR13: System can detect merge conflicts from failed git merge\n33\t- FR14: System can dispatch a merge agent with conflict context from both branches\n34\t- FR15: System can run the full test suite on the merged result before accepting\n35\t- FR16: System can reject a merge and escalate if tests fail after resolution\n36\t- FR17: User can configure merge strategy (rebase or merge-commit)\n37\t- FR18: System can execute tasks with agent: null directly without LLM dispatch\n38\t- FR19: System can collect structured telemetry data per story\n39\t- FR20: System can write telemetry entries as NDJSON to .codeharness/telemetry.jsonl\n40\t- FR21: System can read telemetry entries for a specific epic and inject as retro context\n41\t- FR22: System can detect when all stories in an epic have reached done status\n42\t- FR23: System can trigger epic_flow tasks on epic completion\n43\t- FR24: System can track epic-level state separately from story-level state\n44\t- FR25: System can set tests_passed and coverage_met flags from dev task output contract\n45\t- FR26: System can skip coverage re-run during verification if coverage exists in contract\n46\t- FR27: System can render multiple concurrent workflow graphs in the Ink TUI\n47\t- FR28: System can display a summary bar showing active lanes, total cost, merge status\n48\t- FR29: System can show merge progress and conflict resolution status in the TUI\n49\t- FR30: System can render lane completion as a distinct visual state\n50\t\n51\t### Non-Functional Requirements\n52\t\n53\t- NFR1-NFR5: Performance (worktree <10s, TUI 15 FPS, telemetry <10ms, merge <30s)\n54\t- NFR6-NFR10: Reliability (crash isolation, merge retry limit, state consistency, orphan cleanup, backward compat)\n55\t- NFR11-NFR13: Integration (git hooks compat, branch prefix, telemetry format stability)\n56\t\n57\t### FR Coverage Map\n58\t\n59\t| FR | Epic | Description |\n60\t|----|------|-------------|\n61\t| FR1 | Epic 16 | Hierarchical flow YAML sections |\n62\t| FR2 | Epic 16 | Parse/validate with backward compat |\n63\t| FR3 | Epic 16 | Execute story-level flow |\n64\t| FR4 | Epic 16 | Execute epic-level flow |\n65\t| FR5 | Epic 16 | Schedule epics by strategy |\n66\t| FR6 | Epic 17 | Create git worktree per epic |\n67\t| FR7 | Epic 17 | Create git branch per epic |\n68\t| FR8 | Epic 17 | Execute stories in worktree |\n69\t| FR9 | Epic 17 | Lane pool with max_parallel |\n70\t| FR10 | Epic 17 | Detect epic independence |\n71\t| FR11 | Epic 17 | Clean up worktrees/branches |\n72\t| FR12 | Epic 18 | Merge epic branch to main |\n73\t| FR13 | Epic 18 | Detect merge conflicts |\n74\t| FR14 | Epic 18 | Dispatch merge agent |\n75\t| FR15 | Epic 18 | Cross-worktree test validation |\n76\t| FR16 | Epic 18 | Reject merge + escalate |\n77\t| FR17 | Epic 18 | Configure merge strategy |\n78\t| FR18 | Epic 16 | agent: null execution |\n79\t| FR19 | Epic 16 | Collect telemetry data |\n80\t| FR20 | Epic 16 | Write telemetry NDJSON |\n81\t| FR21 | Epic 16 | Read telemetry for retro injection |\n82\t| FR22 | Epic 19 | Detect epic completion |\n83\t| FR23 | Epic 19 | Trigger epic_flow |\n84\t| FR24 | Epic 19 | Track epic-level state |\n85\t| FR25 | Epic 16 | Engine sets verify flags |\n86\t| FR26 | Epic 16 | Coverage deduplication |\n87\t| FR27 | Epic 20 | Multi-lane workflow graphs |\n88\t| FR28 | Epic 20 | Summary bar |\n89\t| FR29 | Epic 20 | Merge status in TUI |\n90\t| FR30 | Epic 20 | Lane completion visual state |\n91\t\n92\t## Epic List\n93\t\n94\t### Epic 16: Hierarchical Flow Model & Engine-Handled Tasks\n95\tUsers can define story_flow, epic_flow, and execution sections in workflow YAML. Tasks with agent: null execute directly in the engine. Existing flat flow: still works. Verify flags set from output contract.\n96\t**FRs covered:** FR1, FR2, FR3, FR4, FR5, FR18, FR19, FR20, FR21, FR25, FR26\n97\t\n98\t### Epic 17: Worktree Management & Lane Pool\n99\tUsers can run parallel epics in isolated git worktrees. Lane pool schedules epics concurrently up to max_parallel.\n100\t**FRs covered:** FR6, FR7, FR8, FR9, FR10, FR11\n101\t\n102\t### Epic 18: Merge Agent & Cross-Worktree Validation\n103\tEpic branches merge to main with auto-conflict resolution and test validation.\n104\t**FRs covered:** FR12, FR13, FR14, FR15, FR16, FR17\n105\t\n106\t### Epic 19: Epic Completion & Lifecycle\n107\tSystem detects epic completion and triggers epic_flow tasks.\n108\t**FRs covered:** FR22, FR23, FR24\n109\t\n110\t### Epic 20: Multi-Lane TUI\n111\tTUI renders concurrent lanes with merge status and summary bar.\n112\t**FRs covered:** FR27, FR28, FR29, FR30\n113\t\n114\t## Epic 16: Hierarchical Flow Model & Engine-Handled Tasks\n115\t\n116\tUsers can define hierarchical workflows with engine-handled zero-token tasks, verify flag propagation, and telemetry collection.\n117\t\n118\t### Story 16.1: Hierarchical Flow Schema & Parser\n119\t\n120\tAs a user,\n121\tI want to define `execution`, `story_flow`, and `epic_flow` sections in workflow YAML,\n122\tSo that I can configure sprint-level, epic-level, and story-level behavior separately.\n123\t\n124\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n125\t\n126\t**Given** `src/schemas/workflow.schema.json`\n127\t**When** updated with `execution`, `story_flow`, and `epic_flow` sections\n128\t**Then** `execution` supports `max_parallel`, `isolation`, `merge_strategy`, `epic_strategy`, `story_strategy`\n129\t**And** `story_flow` accepts the same format as existing `flow` (task refs + loop blocks)\n130\t**And** `epic_flow` accepts task refs including built-in names `merge` and `validate`\n131\t**And** existing workflows with only `flow:` parse successfully (backward compat — treated as `story_flow`)\n132\t**And** `workflow-parser.ts` resolves hierarchical flow via `hierarchical-flow.ts`\n133\t**And** validation rejects `story_flow` tasks not defined in `tasks:` section\n134\t\n135\t### Story 16.2: Engine-Handled Null Tasks\n136\t\n137\tAs a developer,\n138\tI want tasks with `agent: null` to execute directly in the engine without LLM dispatch,\n139\tSo that telemetry collection and state bookkeeping cost zero tokens.\n140\t\n141\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n142\t\n143\t**Given** a task definition with `agent: null` in workflow YAML\n144\t**When** the workflow engine reaches this task in the flow\n145\t**Then** the engine looks up the task name in the null task handler registry\n146\t**And** calls the handler directly (no driver dispatch, no stream events)\n147\t**And** the handler receives `TaskContext` with story key, cost, duration, output contract\n148\t**And** unknown null task names produce a descriptive error\n149\t**And** null tasks complete in <10ms for data collection operations\n150\t\n151\t### Story 16.3: Telemetry Writer\n152\t\n153\tAs a developer,\n154\tI want structured telemetry written as NDJSON after each story completes,\n155\tSo that epic retros have rich data without per-session LLM cost.\n156\t\n157\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n158\t\n159\t**Given** a new `src/lib/telemetry-writer.ts`\n160\t**When** the `telemetry` null task handler runs after a story\n161\t**Then** it writes one NDJSON line to `.codeharness/telemetry.jsonl`\n162\t**And** each entry includes: version, timestamp, storyKey, epicId, duration_ms, cost_usd, attempts, acResults, filesChanged, testResults, errors\n163\t**And** fields not available are set to `null` (never fabricated)\n164\t**And** writes are append-only with `appendFileSync`\n165\t**And** telemetry entries include `version: 1` for forward compatibility\n166\t**And** a `readTelemetryForEpic(epicId)` function returns all entries for a given epic\n167\t\n168\t### Story 16.4: Verify Flag Propagation\n169\t\n170\tAs a developer,\n171\tI want the engine to set `tests_passed` and `coverage_met` from the dev task's output contract,\n172\tSo that verification doesn't fail on missing flags set by subagents.\n173\t\n174\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n175\t\n176\t**Given** the implement task completes with an output contract containing `testResults`\n177\t**When** `testResults.failed === 0`\n178\t**Then** the engine sets `tests_passed = true` in the state file\n179\t**And** when `testResults.coverage >= coverage.target`\n180\t**Then** the engine sets `coverage_met = true` in the state file\n181\t**And** the verify task no longer needs to set these flags itself\n182\t**And** existing behavior is preserved when output contract has no testResults\n183\t\n184\t### Story 16.5: Coverage Deduplication\n185\t\n186\tAs a developer,\n187\tI want the verify phase to read coverage from the output contract instead of re-running,\n188\tSo that coverage is not computed twice per story.\n189\t\n190\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n191\t\n192\t**Given** the implement task's output contract contains `testResults.coverage`\n193\t**When** the verify task starts\n194\t**Then** if `coverage_met` is already true (set by engine in 16.4), skip coverage re-run\n195\t**And** the evaluator prompt includes coverage result from the contract as context\n196\t**And** if no coverage data exists in the contract, verify runs coverage normally (fallback)\n197\t\n198\t### Story 16.6: Story Flow Execution\n199\t\n200\tAs a developer,\n201\tI want the workflow engine to execute `story_flow` for each story within an epic,\n202\tSo that the hierarchical flow model drives story-level execution.\n203\t\n204\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n205\t\n206\t**Given** a workflow with `story_flow: [implement, verify, loop: [retry, verify], telemetry]`\n207\t**When** the engine processes an epic's stories\n208\t**Then** each story runs through the complete story_flow pipeline\n209\t**And** the `telemetry` null task runs after verify completes (or after loop exits)\n210\t**And** story_flow respects existing loop semantics (max iterations, circuit breaker)\n211\t**And** backward compat: workflows with `flow:` (no `story_flow`) produce identical behavior\n212\t\n213\t## Epic 17: Worktree Management & Lane Pool\n214\t\n215\tUsers can run epics in parallel using git worktree isolation with configurable concurrency.\n216\t\n217\t### Story 17.1: Worktree Manager\n218\t\n219\tAs a developer,\n220\tI want a worktree manager that handles git worktree create/merge/cleanup,\n221\tSo that parallel epics run in isolated working directories.\n222\t\n223\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n224\t\n225\t**Given** a new `src/lib/worktree-manager.ts`\n226\t**When** `createWorktree(epicId, slug)` is called\n227\t**Then** it creates branch `codeharness/epic-{N}-{slug}` from main\n228\t**And** creates worktree at `/tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-{N}`\n229\t**And** returns the worktree path\n230\t**And** creation completes within 10 seconds (NFR1)\n231\t**And** `cleanupWorktree(epicId)` removes worktree and deletes branch\n232\t**And** `listWorktrees()` returns all active codeharness worktrees\n233\t**And** orphaned worktrees (from previous crashed runs) are detected and reported\n234\t\n235\t### Story 17.2: Lane Pool\n236\t\n237\tAs a developer,\n238\tI want a lane pool that schedules epics concurrently up to `max_parallel`,\n239\tSo that the engine runs multiple epics simultaneously.\n240\t\n241\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n242\t\n243\t**Given** a new `src/lib/lane-pool.ts`\n244\t**When** `startPool(epics, maxParallel)` is called\n245\t**Then** it creates up to `maxParallel` lanes simultaneously\n246\t**And** each lane creates a worktree and runs the workflow engine for that epic's stories\n247\t**And** `Promise.race` on active lanes detects completion\n248\t**And** when a lane completes, the next independent epic is scheduled\n249\t**And** epic independence is determined by epic ordering (epic N only if no epic < N is active, except done)\n250\t**And** the pool emits `LaneEvent` objects for TUI consumption\n251\t**And** `maxParallel: 1` produces sequential execution identical to current behavior (NFR10)\n252\t\n253\t### Story 17.3: Run Command Parallel Integration\n254\t\n255\tAs a user,\n256\tI want `codeharness run` to use the lane pool when `execution.epic_strategy: parallel`,\n257\tSo that parallel execution works end-to-end.\n258\t\n259\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n260\t\n261\t**Given** a workflow with `execution: { max_parallel: 2, epic_strategy: parallel }`\n262\t**When** `codeharness run` executes\n263\t**Then** the run command reads `execution` config from the resolved workflow\n264\t**And** creates a lane pool with `max_parallel` from config\n265\t**And** passes all pending epics (from sprint state) to the pool\n266\t**And** stories within each epic execute sequentially in their worktree\n267\t**And** crash in one lane does not affect other lanes (NFR6)\n268\t**And** the run command reports final results from all lanes\n269\t\n270\t## Epic 18: Merge Agent & Cross-Worktree Validation\n271\t\n272\tEpic branches merge to main with automated conflict resolution and test validation.\n273\t\n274\t### Story 18.1: Merge Serialization & Execution\n275\t\n276\tAs a developer,\n277\tI want epic branches to merge into main one at a time with full test validation,\n278\tSo that merged code is always tested and conflicts don't race.\n279\t\n280\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n281\t\n282\t**Given** `worktree-manager.ts` gains `mergeWorktree(epicId)` method\n283\t**When** an epic completes and merge is triggered\n284\t**Then** a mutex ensures only one merge runs at a time\n285\t**And** `git merge codeharness/epic-{N}-{slug}` executes on main\n286\t**And** if merge succeeds (no conflicts), the full test suite runs on merged result\n287\t**And** if tests pass, worktree is cleaned up\n288\t**And** merge completes within 30 seconds for non-conflicting cases (NFR4)\n289\t**And** user can configure merge strategy (rebase or merge-commit) via `execution.merge_strategy`\n290\t\n291\t### Story 18.2: Merge Agent for Conflict Resolution\n292\t\n293\tAs a developer,\n294\tI want a merge agent that resolves git conflicts with semantic context,\n295\tSo that parallel epics don't require manual conflict resolution.\n296\t\n297\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n298\t\n299\t**Given** a new `src/lib/merge-agent.ts`\n300\t**When** `git merge` returns conflicts\n301\t**Then** the merge agent is dispatched with: conflicting files, main content, branch content, both epics' descriptions\n302\t**And** the agent resolves conflicts by understanding what both epics built\n303\t**And** after resolution, the test suite runs on the merged result\n304\t**And** if tests fail, the merge is reverted and the agent retries (up to 3 attempts)\n305\t**And** after 3 failures, the merge is escalated: worktree and branch preserved, user notified with instructions\n306\t**And** escalation message includes: worktree path, branch name, conflicting files, and `git diff` command\n307\t\n308\t### Story 18.3: Cross-Worktree Test Validation\n309\t\n310\tAs a developer,\n311\tI want the full test suite to run after every merge,\n312\tSo that merged code is proven to work before accepting.\n313\t\n314\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n315\t\n316\t**Given** a successful merge (clean or agent-resolved)\n317\t**When** the test suite runs on the merged main\n318\t**Then** all tests must pass for the merge to be accepted\n319\t**And** if tests fail after clean merge, the merge is reverted and escalated immediately\n320\t**And** if tests fail after agent resolution, revert and retry agent with test failure context\n321\t**And** test suite runs within the project's configured test timeout\n322\t**And** test results (pass/fail count, coverage) are logged to telemetry\n323\t\n324\t## Epic 19: Epic Completion & Lifecycle\n325\t\n326\tSystem detects epic completion and triggers epic_flow tasks in sequence.\n327\t\n328\t### Story 19.1: Epic Completion Detection\n329\t\n330\tAs a developer,\n331\tI want the engine to detect when all stories in an epic are done,\n332\tSo that epic_flow tasks are triggered automatically.\n333\t\n334\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n335\t\n336\t**Given** a new `src/lib/epic-completion.ts`\n337\t**When** a story reaches `done` status\n338\t**Then** the engine checks if all stories in that epic are `done`\n339\t**And** if yes, the epic state transitions from `in-progress` to `completing`\n340\t**And** `epic_flow` tasks are triggered in sequence (retro → merge → validate)\n341\t**And** epic state tracks: `in-progress → completing → merging → validating → done`\n342\t**And** if merge fails, epic state becomes `failed` (worktree preserved)\n343\t\n344\t### Story 19.2: Epic Flow Execution\n345\t\n346\tAs a developer,\n347\tI want `epic_flow` tasks to execute in sequence when an epic completes,\n348\tSo that retro, merge, and validate happen automatically.\n349\t\n350\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n351\t\n352\t**Given** an epic reaches `completing` state\n353\t**When** `epic_flow` is `[retro, merge, validate]`\n354\t**Then** `retro` dispatches the analyst agent with telemetry data for this epic (from FR21)\n355\t**And** `merge` calls `worktree-manager.mergeWorktree()` (built-in, no agent)\n356\t**And** `validate` runs the test suite on merged result (built-in, no agent)\n357\t**And** each step updates epic state (completing → merging → validating → done)\n358\t**And** if any step fails, subsequent steps are skipped and epic is marked `failed`\n359\t**And** the lane is freed for the next epic after completion or failure\n360\t\n361\t## Epic 20: Multi-Lane TUI\n362\t\n363\tTUI renders concurrent lanes with merge status and responsive layout.\n364\t\n365\t### Story 20.1: Lane Container & Lane Components\n366\t\n367\tAs a user,\n368\tI want to see multiple epic lanes in the TUI during parallel execution,\n369\tSo that I can track progress across all active worktrees.\n370\t\n371\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n372\t\n373\t**Given** new `src/lib/ink-lane.tsx` and `src/lib/ink-lane-container.tsx`\n374\t**When** 2 lanes are active\n375\t**Then** the TUI renders lanes side-by-side (terminal >= 120 cols) or stacked (80-119 cols) or single (<80 cols)\n376\t**And** each lane shows: epic title, current story + phase, story progress bar, driver + cost/time\n377\t**And** lanes 3+ collapse to one-line summaries: `Lane N: Epic Title │ story ◆ phase │ $cost / time`\n378\t**And** single lane mode (`max_parallel: 1`) renders identically to current single-lane TUI\n379\t\n380\t### Story 20.2: Summary Bar & Merge Status\n381\t\n382\tAs a user,\n383\tI want to see done/merging/pending counts and merge progress in the TUI,\n384\tSo that I know the sprint's overall state at a glance.\n385\t\n386\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n387\t\n388\t**Given** new `src/lib/ink-summary-bar.tsx` and `src/lib/ink-merge-status.tsx`\n389\t**When** rendered between lanes and activity section\n390\t**Then** summary bar shows: `Done: X stories │ Merging: epic-N → main ◌ │ Pending: epic-A, epic-B`\n391\t**And** merge status shows: merge in progress (spinner), clean merge (green), conflict resolving (yellow), escalated (red)\n392\t**And** post-merge test results shown: pass count, coverage\n393\t**And** lane completion event: `[OK] Lane N: Epic X complete (stories, cost, time)`\n394\t\n395\t### Story 20.3: Lane Event Routing & Activity Display\n396\t\n397\tAs a user,\n398\tI want the activity section to show the most recently active lane's tool calls,\n399\tSo that I can see what's happening without noise from all lanes.\n400\t\n401\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n402\t\n403\t**Given** the existing activity display (tool calls, thoughts, retries)\n404\t**When** multiple lanes are producing stream events\n405\t**Then** the activity section shows events from the most recently active lane only\n406\t**And** the active lane is indicated: `[Lane 1 ▸]` in the activity header\n407\t**And** `Ctrl+L` cycles which lane's activity is displayed\n408\t**And** TUI remains responsive at 15 FPS with up to 4 concurrent lanes (NFR2)\n409\t**And** a crashed lane does not freeze the TUI (NFR6 — event stream ends, lane marked failed)\n410\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01CHrkgpjhvPg7eJ8iLesM4b","session_id":"22206bba-5847-41b1-b510-883e1dd8c0da","uuid":"2e51d5e1-30fc-42b2-b2b8-e83824870939","timestamp":"2026-04-03T22:07:53.637Z"}
